Global Airbnb Insights: A Comparative Study of New York, Paris, and Tokyos Rental Markets and Trends

Author: Pietro Tegon

Introduction: Airbnb's adaptability across cities

Airbnb, founded in 2008, has rapidly transformed the landscape of global travel and accommodation. As an online marketplace, it connects hosts offering unique lodging spaces with travelers seeking alternatives to traditional hotels. By leveraging technology, Airbnb has enabled millions of people to monetize their homes and share their local cultures with guests from around the world. This innovative model not only provides travelers with a variety of lodging options, ranging from budget-friendly rooms to luxury villas, but also fosters a more authentic travel experience by immersing guests in local communities.. This project examines the influence and use of Airbnb in three major cities across three different continents: Paris, Tokyo, and New York. Each city presents a unique cultural and social landscape, demonstrating how Airbnb adapts to diverse environments.

In Paris, the romantic and historic ambiance of the city is reflected in the variety of accommodations offered, allowing travelers to experience the citys charm from within its neighborhoods. Tokyo, a city that blends the ultramodern with the traditional, provides a different dynamic, where Airbnb enables visitors to enjoy a local experience amidst the citys fast-paced environment. New York City, known for its cultural diversity and vibrant urban life, showcases Airbnbs ability to cater to a wide range of tastes and preferences, offering everything from trendy apartments in Manhattan to cozy spaces in Brooklyn.

This projects examines the differences in Airbnb stays in these three cities, which can range from price to type of stay to the difference between neighboorhoods within each city. Additionally, each city's Airbnbs will be examined on their own, to better understand trends, internal differences between neighborhoods or correlation between price and other variables.

Datasets

  • listings_paris.csv
  • listings_tokyo.csv
  • reviews_paris.csv
  • reviews_tokyo.csv
  • reviews_ny.csv

Source: https://insideairbnb.com/get-the-data/

  • Airbnb_Open_Data_ny.csv

Source: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/arianazmoudeh/airbnbopendata

Research questions

The questions that will be used as guidelines throughout this notebook are:

  • What are the differences between the three cities?
  • For each city, are there internal differences? Which ones?
  • Which trends in tourism or price have these cities been following?

The selection of the datasets and all the steps taken towards the analysis of the data will be functional to the answer of the research questions.

These are the selected columns:

  • ID: Unique identifier for each Airbnb listing.
  • Neighbourhood: The specific area or district where the listing is located within the city.
  • Latitude: Geographic latitude coordinate of the listing's location.
  • Longitude: Geographic longitude coordinate of the listing's location.
  • Room Type: Type of accommodation offered (e.g., entire home, private room, shared room).
  • Price: Cost per night in local currency for staying at the listing.
  • Minimum Nights: The minimum number of nights required to book the listing.
  • Last Review: The date of the most recent review left by a guest.
  • Reviews per Month: Average number of reviews the listing receives each month.
  • Availability 365: Number of days the listing is available for booking throughout the year.

The only differences are:

  • Neighbourhood Group: Broader area or district classification within the city, grouping similar neighbourhoods together.
  • Construction Year: The year in which the building housing the Airbnb listing was constructed.
  • Service Fee: Additional fee charged by Airbnb to cover service and support costs, typically added to the total booking price.

The columns service fee and price contain some $ symbols, which make the entries strings, so I will need to strip the string characters and turn the numbers into floats.

In[800]:
# Remove '$' signs and ',' commas, then convert to float for 'price'
airbnb_newyork['price'] = airbnb_newyork['price'].str.replace('[\$,]', '', regex=True).astype(float)

# Remove '$' signs and ',' commas, then convert to float for 'service fee'
airbnb_newyork['service fee'] = airbnb_newyork['service fee'].str.replace('[\$,]', '', regex=True).astype(float)

The neighborhood situation is very different. I will take the first 500 rows from the sorted dataset for the neighborhoods with more than 500 entries, while i will delete the neighborhoods with less than 100 stays: this is because a neighborhood with very few stays could have outliers and influence the results of the analysis. In general statistic analysis needs a sufficient quantity of data to be efficient and thruthful.

New York is clearly the most expensive city on average, doubling Paris and more than tripling Tokyo. New York's Airbnb rentals tend to be more expensive on average compared to those in Tokyo and Paris due to several factors. Firstly, New York City's real estate market is notoriously pricey, driving up the cost of both long-term and short-term rentals. Additionally, the high demand for short-term accommodations in such a bustling, tourist-heavy city further inflates prices. In contrast, Tokyo and Paris, while also popular destinations, benefit from different economic conditions, regulatory environments, and housing markets that can offer relatively more affordable rental options.

Despite New York's Airbnb rentals being more expensive in absolute terms, when comparing prices relative to the average national monthly salary, Paris stands out as having a higher ratio. This discrepancy arises because the cost of living in Paris, including housing costs, is relatively high compared to the average wages in France. Parisian salaries often do not keep pace with the cost of living, leading to a greater percentage of income being spent on accommodation. Conversely, New York's higher absolute rental prices are somewhat mitigated by generally higher salaries, which balance out the percentage of income spent on housing. Tokyo also benefits from a relatively balanced ratio between rental prices and average incomes, making its Airbnb costs more manageable in comparison to Paris.

Correlation between distance from city center and price

In[846]:
# Define the city center coordinates (Notre-Dame Cathedral)
city_center_lat = 48.8566
city_center_lon = 2.3522

# Function to calculate distance using Haversine formula
def haversine_distance(lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2):
    R = 6371  # Earth radius in kilometers
    lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2 = map(np.radians, [lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2])
    dlat = lat2 - lat1
    dlon = lon2 - lon1
    a = np.sin(dlat/2)**2 + np.cos(lat1) * np.cos(lat2) * np.sin(dlon/2)**2
    c = 2 * np.arcsin(np.sqrt(a))
    return R * c

# Calculate distance from city center for each listing
merged_paris['distance_from_center'] = merged_paris.apply(
    lambda row: haversine_distance(city_center_lat, city_center_lon, row['latitude'], row['longitude']), axis=1
)

# Calculate correlation between price and distance
correlation = merged_paris[['price', 'distance_from_center']].corr()
print("Correlation between price and distance from city center:")
print(correlation)

# Plot the relationship between price and distance
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.scatterplot(data=merged_paris, x='distance_from_center', y='price')
plt.xlabel('Distance from City Center (km)')
plt.ylabel('Price')
plt.title('Price vs. Distance from City Center')
plt.show()

price                 1.000000             -0.017459
distance_from_center -0.017459              1.000000

This is probably because each neighborhood has some expensive stays, maybe because of the amenities, maybe because of different benefits, such as being close to the subway, which in Paris is a good and cheap way to move around the city.

Correlation between distance from city center and price

In[851]:
# Define the city center coordinates (Chiyoda City, near Imperial Palace)
city_center_lat_tokyo = 35.682839
city_center_lon_tokyo = 139.759455

# Function to calculate distance using Haversine formula (reuse from previous example)
def haversine_distance(lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2):
    R = 6371  # Earth radius in kilometers
    lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2 = map(np.radians, [lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2])
    dlat = lat2 - lat1
    dlon = lon2 - lon1
    a = np.sin(dlat/2)**2 + np.cos(lat1) * np.cos(lat2) * np.sin(dlon/2)**2
    c = 2 * np.arcsin(np.sqrt(a))
    return R * c

# Calculate distance from city center for each listing in Tokyo
merged_tokyo['distance_from_center'] = merged_tokyo.apply(
    lambda row: haversine_distance(city_center_lat_tokyo, city_center_lon_tokyo, row['latitude'], row['longitude']), axis=1
)

# Calculate correlation between price and distance
correlation_tokyo = merged_tokyo[['price', 'distance_from_center']].corr()
print("Correlation between price and distance from city center in Tokyo (using Chiyoda as center):")
print(correlation_tokyo)

# Plot the relationship between price and distance

plt.ylabel('Price')

Conclusions

This analysis reveals distinct differences in the Airbnb rental markets of New York, Paris, and Tokyo, driven by each citys unique real estate landscape, economic conditions, and tourism demands. New York stands out as the most expensive city, with Airbnb prices that are significantly higher than those in Paris and Tokyo. This is due to the citys costly real estate, high demand from international tourists, and preference for entire homes/apartments over other types of accommodations. Paris, while less expensive in absolute terms than New York, has a higher cost-to-income ratio due to the relatively high cost of living and moderate wages. In Paris, luxury hotel rooms are more prevalent, reflecting the citys reputation for historic and high-end accommodations. Tokyo offers the most balanced market, with affordable rental prices relative to incomes, driven by a preference for hotels and a well-developed infrastructure catering to both local and international tourists.

Within each city, internal disparities are evident. In New York, Manhattan leads with the highest prices, followed by Brooklyn, while Queens, the Bronx, and Staten Island offer more budget-friendly options. Paris showcases a divide between expensive central areas like Palais-Bourbon and more affordable neighborhoods like Mnilmontant. In Tokyo, upscale areas such as Shibuya Ku command higher prices, whereas residential districts like Nakano Ku offer more affordable options.

All three cities have shown an upward trend in Airbnb prices over the past decade, with New York demonstrating resilience during the pandemic. Seasonal fluctuations affect pricing, with New York peaking in summer and Tokyo during late spring. Across all cities, entire homes/apartments are consistently more expensive than private rooms or shared spaces, indicating a strong preference for privacy and space among travelers.
